According to a new report from Intel Market Research, the global Silicon Bronze (C70250) market was valued at USD 49.03 million in 2026 and is projected to reach USD 85.94 million by 2034, exhibiting a robust CAGR of 8.6% during the forecast period (2026‑2034). This growth is propelled by expanding demand for high‑performance copper‑based alloys in lightweight automotive and aerospace platforms, intensified infrastructure development that calls for corrosion‑resistant components, and the rising penetration of silicon bronze in electrical, marine and renewable‑energy applications.
Silicon Bronze (C70250) is a high‑performance copper alloy belonging to the Corson family, composed primarily of copper, silicon and nickel. The addition of silicon imparts solid‑solution strengthening, delivering superior tensile strength and wear resistance, while nickel refines the grain structure and enhances hardness. The alloy’s balanced property matrix-mechanical robustness, excellent electrical conductivity, and outstanding resistance to seawater corrosion-makes it a versatile material for both functional engineering parts and decorative architectural elements.
